05168nam a22007695i 9781400834372DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20102010nju    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)999367049  a97814008343727 a10.1515/97814008343722doi  a(DE-B1597)446615  a(OCoLC)979745370  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aHIS0370702bisacsh04a305.5/520944090461 aWolin, Richard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Wind from the East :bFrench Intellectuals, the Cultural Revolution, and the Legacy of the 1960s /cRichard Wolin.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (408 p.) :b6 halftones.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrologue -- tIntroduction. The Maoist Temptation -- tPart I. The Hour of Rebellion -- tChapter 1. Showdown at Bruay-en-Artois -- tChapter 2. France during the 1960s -- tChapter 3. May 1968: The Triumph of Libidinal Politics -- tChapter 4. Who Were the Maoists? -- tExcursus. On the Sectarian Maoism of Alain Badiou -- tPart 2. The Hour of the Intellectuals -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 5. Jean-Paul Sartre’s Perfect Maoist Moment -- tChapter 6. Tel Quel in Cultural-Political Hell -- tChapter 7. Foucault and the Maoists: Biopolitics and Engagement -- tChapter 8. The Impossible Heritage: From Cultural Revolution to Associational Democracy -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMichel Foucault, Jean-Paul Sartre, Julia Kristeva, Phillipe Sollers, and Jean-Luc Godard. During the 1960s, a who's who of French thinkers, writers, and artists, spurred by China's Cultural Revolution, were seized with a fascination for Maoism. Combining a merciless exposé of left-wing political folly and cross-cultural misunderstanding with a spirited defense of the 1960s, The Wind from the East tells the colorful story of this legendary period in France. Richard Wolin shows how French students and intellectuals, inspired by their perceptions of the Cultural Revolution, and motivated by utopian hopes, incited grassroots social movements and reinvigorated French civic and cultural life. Wolin's riveting narrative reveals that Maoism's allure among France's best and brightest actually had little to do with a real understanding of Chinese politics. Instead, it paradoxically served as a vehicle for an emancipatory transformation of French society. French student leftists took up the trope of "cultural revolution," applying it to their criticisms of everyday life. Wolin examines how Maoism captured the imaginations of France's leading cultural figures, influencing Sartre's "perfect Maoist moment"; Foucault's conception of power; Sollers's chic, leftist intellectual journal Tel Quel; as well as Kristeva's book on Chinese women--which included a vigorous defense of foot-binding. Recounting the cultural and political odyssey of French students and intellectuals in the 1960s, The Wind from the East illustrates how the Maoist phenomenon unexpectedly sparked a democratic political sea change in France.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aChinaxHistoryvCultural Revolution, 1966-1976vInfluence. 0aCommunismzFrancexHistoryx20th century. 0aCommunismzFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aFrancevIntellectual lifex20th century. 0aHISTORYzEuropezFrance. 0aIntellectualsvPolitical activityzFrancexHistoryx20th century. 0aIntellectualsvPolitical activity. 0aIntellectualsxPolitical activityzFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aIntellectualszFrancexHistoryx20th century. 0aIntellectualszFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aMao, ZedongvInfluence. 0aSOCIAL SCIENCEvSocial Classes. 7aHISTORY